			<div id="tabContent" >
				<div class="content defaultmsg">
					<h5><em><: l('Select an item from the left to learn more about it.') :></em></h5>
				</div>
				<div id="cookies" class="content active">
					<h5><: l('HTTP Cookies') :></h5>
					<p><: l('HTTP cookies or "browser cookies" are small pieces of data sent between your Web browser and a Web site, commonly used to track users, even across multiple Web sites.') :> <: l("Cookies can be used to help build a profile about you based on the links you've clicked and other actions you've taken on various Web sites.") :> <: l('These profiles can then be used to serve personalized advertisements and search results.') :> <: l('However, cookies can also be used for non-tracking purposes, such as storing user settings or keeping you logged in.') :></p>				
					<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Http_cookie" target="wiki"><: l('Learn more about %s', 'Cookies') :></a></p>
					<p><: l('To fix, look for this icon in the above and below sections:') :> <span class="type-preview"><i class="icon cookies"></i></span></p>
				</div>
				<div id="flash-cookies" class="content">
					<h5><: l('Flash Cookies') :></h5>
					<p><:l("Flash Cookies are a lot like regular browser cookies in that they are small pieces of data stored on a user's computer by a Web site."):> <:l('Similar to browser HTTP cookies, flash cookies can be used to collect data about you and your Web activity.'):> <:l('Also called "LSOs" (Locally Shared Objects), flash cookies are added to your computer when you visit a Web site that uses Adobe Flash.'):> <:l("Unlike browser cookies, Flash cookies are not stored in the same location on your computer and are rarely mentioned in Web sites' privacy policies."):></p>				
					<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_Shared_Object" target="wiki"><: l('Learn more about %s', 'Flash Cookies') :></a></p>
					<p><: l('To fix, look for this icon in the above and below sections:') :> <span class="type-preview"><i class="icon flashcookies"></i></span></p>
				</div>
				<div id="scripts" class="content">
					<h5><: l('Scripts') :></h5>
					<p><: l('Script vulnerabilites are most commonly in the form of JavaScript exploits.'):> <: l("JavaScript is a type of programming language commonly used on Web sites and web applications but can be used to maliciously attack a user's computer through what is known as Cross-site scripting (or XSS)."):> <: l('This is where an attacker places a malicious piece of code (the script) on a seemingly benign Web site.'):> <: l("After the user enters information or clicks on a link, the script is carried out and the user's information or activity can be logged by the attacker."):> <: l('Many browsers allow you to disable JavaScript but, as many modern Web sites employ JavaScript, it may cause a loss in the functionality of your browser.'):> </p>				
					<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JavaScript#Security" target="wiki"><: l('Learn more about %s', 'Javascript Security') :></a></p>
					<p><: l('To fix, look for this icon in the above and below sections:') :> <span class="type-preview"><i class="icon scripts"></i></span></p>
				</div>
				<div id="encryption" class="content">
					<h5><: l('Web Encryption') :></h5>
					<p><: l('You can recognize a secure (Web encrypted) site by its HTTPS:// prefix.'):> <: l('Standard sites (non-secure) begin with HTTP://.'):> <: l('Web Sites that use HTTPS are ensuring that the communication between them and their users are authenticated in a secure environment and are therefore safer against eavesdropping from attackers.'):> <: l('This can be thought of as the sender of a message scrambling the letters of a document.'):> <: l('The recipient can only read the document if they have the key to unscramble the message.'):></p>				
					<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTTP_Secure" target="wiki"><: l('Learn more about %s', 'Web Encryption') :></a></p>
					<p><: l('To fix, look for this icon in the above and below sections:') :> <span class="type-preview"><i class="icon encryption"></i></span></p>
				</div>
				<div id="bugs" class="content">
					<h5><: l('Web Bugs') :></h5>
					<p><: l('Web bugs are mechanisms to track specific user activities on Web sites.'):> <: l('Often unknown to the user, web bugs (also called "tracking bugs") can come in many different forms such as hidden images.'):> <: l('For example, when spam mail is sent out to millions of random addresses, web bugs are often included to track which e-mail addresses are valid by monitoring which messages were opened.'):> </p>				
					<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_bugs" target="wiki"><: l('Learn more about %s', 'Web Bugs') :></a></p>
					<p><: l('To fix, look for this icon in the above and below sections:') :> <span class="type-preview"><i class="icon bugs"></i></span></p>
				</div>
				<div id="referrer-tracking" class="content">
					<h5><: l('Referrer Tracking') :></h5>
					<p><: l('Web sites can track where their traffic is coming from through the use of referrers (aka HTTP referers).') :> <: l("Through HTTP referrers, it's possible to tell which site a user has just come from, and can also include other user information, sometimes personal (like search terms).") :> </p>				
					<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTTP_REFERER" target="wiki"><: l('Learn more about %s', 'Referrer Tracking') :></a></p>
					<p><: l('To fix, look for this icon in the above and below sections:') :> <span class="type-preview"><i class="icon referrer"></i></span></p>
				</div>
				<div id="browser-fingerprinting" class="content">
					<h5><: l('Browser Fingerprinting') :></h5>
					<p><: l('Web Sites and 3rd party trackers can gather information about your browser to uniquely identify you and therefore track you.'):> <: l('Things like browser settings, installed plugins, installed fonts, and IP configuration are often combined to create a unique fingerprint that can be used to link users to their devices.'):> <: l('A related example would be tracking a person through their physical attributes.'):> <: l("It's difficult to find someone based on 1 descriptor like gender."):> <: l('Adding in other descriptors like--blonde hair, 5ft 7in tall, snake tattoo, and red dress--make it a lot easier to identify that person.'):></p>				
					<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Device_fingerprint" target="wiki"><: l('Learn more about %s', 'Browser Fingerprinting') :></a></p>
					<p><: l('Currently, there are no consistent methods to shield yourself from browser fingerprinting.') :> <: l("The Electronic Frontier Foundation has created a tool for you to test and learn about your browser's uniqueness."):> <: l('Check out: %s', r('<a href="http://panopticlick.eff.org/" target="_EFF">') ~ 'https://panopticlick.eff' ~ r('</a>')):></p>
				</div>
				<div id="settings" class="content">
					<h5><: l('Privacy Settings') :></h5>
					<p><: l('Web sites and Web browsers often have settings that can impact your privacy, many which may be on by default.'):> <: l('It is therefore useful to review these settings to see if their tracking outweighs their benefits for you personally.'):></p>
					<p><: l('To fix, look for this icon in the above and below sections:') :> <span class="type-preview"><i class="icon settings"></i></span></p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
		